4x -5 \)</p><p>\( (x^{2} –11x  + 8 =   0 \)</p><p>Since this is of the form \(ax^{2} + bx + c = 0\),this is a quadratic equation</p><p><strong>vi)\( x^{2} + 3x + 1 = (x – 2)^{2} \)</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>\( x^{2} + 3x + 1 = x^{2} –4x + 4 \)</p><p>\(  7x - 3 =    4 \)</p><p>Since this is not of the form \(ax^{2} + bx + c = 0\),this is not  a quadratic equation,a cant be zero,b and c can be zero</p><p><strong>vii)\( (x + 2)^{3} = 2x (x^{2} – 1) \)</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>\( (x + 2)^{3} = 2x (x^{2} – 1) \)</p><p>\( x^{3} + 8 + 6x^{2} + 12x = 2x^{3} – 2x \)</p><p>\( x^{3} + 8 + 6x^{2} + 12x = 2x^{3} – 2x \)</p><p>\( x^{3} + 8 + 6x^{2} + 12x = 2x^{3} – 2x \)</p><p>\( -x^{3} + 8 + 6x^{2} + 14x = 0  \)</p><p>Since this is not of the form \(ax^{2} + bx + c = 0\),this is not  a quadratic equation</p><p><strong>viii)\( x^{3} – 4x^{2} – x + 1 = (x – 2)^{3} \)</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>\( x^{3} – 4x^{2} – x + 1 = (x – 2)^{3} \)</p><p>\( x^{3} – 4x^{2} – x + 1 = x^{3} – 8 -6x^{2} + 12x \)</p><p>\(  2x^{2} – 13x + 9 =  0   \)</p><p>Since this is of the form \(ax^{2} + bx + c = 0\),this is a quadratic equation</p><p><strong>Represent the following in the form of quadratic equations:</strong></p><p><strong>i)The area of a rectangular plot is 528 m 2 . The length of the plot (in metres) is onemore than twice its breadth. We need to find the length and breadth of the plot.</strong></p><p>Let, <strong>x</strong> be <strong>length</strong> (meters) and <strong>y</strong> be <strong>breadth</strong> (meter) of the rectangular plot</p><p>Now, according to given condition:-</p><p><strong>x = 1 + 2y ……… (1)</strong></p><p>And</p><p><strong>x.y = 528m<sup>2</sup>…… (2)</strong></p><p>Now, substituting equation (1) in (2) we get</p><p>(1 + 2y) y = 860</p><p>2y<sup>2 </sup>+ y = 528</p><p><strong>2y<sup>2 </sup>+ y – 528 = 0</strong> where y = breadth (in meters)</p><p><strong>This is the required quadratic equation.</strong></p><p><strong><em>The product of two consecutive positive integers is 306. We need to find the integers</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</em></strong></p><p>Let the consecutive positive integers be x and x + 1</p><p>Now, according to given condition:-</p><p><strong>x(x + 1)= 306 ……… (1)</strong></p><p>x<sup>2</sup> + x= 306</p><p>x<sup>2</sup> + x - 306 = 0</p><p><strong>This is the required quadratic equation.</strong></p><p><strong><em>iii)Rohan’s mother is 26 years older than him. The product of their ages (in years)3 years from now will be 360. We would like to find Rohan’s present age.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Sol.</strong></p><p>Let the present age of Rohan be <strong>x</strong> <strong>years</strong></p><p>Then, present age of Rohans’s mother will be = <strong>(x + 26) years</strong></p><p>Now, their ages after 3 years:</p><p>Rahul’s age = <strong>(x + 3) years</strong></p><p>Rahul’s mother age = x + 26 + 3 = <strong>(x + 29) years</strong></p><p>According to given condition:</p><p>(x+3) (x+29) = 360</p><p>x<sup>2</sup> + 29x +3x + 87 – 360 = 0</p><p><strong>               x<sup>2 </sup>+ 32x – 273 = 0</strong>. (Where x is the present age of Rahul in years)</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup> +39x - 7x – 273 = 0</p><p>x = -39 or x = 7 </p> <p>so present age of Rohan is 7 years</p><p><strong><em>iv)A train travels a distance of 480 km at a uniform speed. If the speed had been8 km/h less, then it would have taken 3 hours more to cover the same distance. Weneed to find the speed of the train.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p><strong>Sol.</strong></p><p>Let the train travels at the uniform speed of <strong>x km/hr.</strong></p><p>Therefore,</p><p>Time taken to cover 480km = <strong>\(\frac{480}{x}hours\)</strong></p><p>Now,</p><p>When speed is reduced by 8km/h then time taken to cover the same distance = <strong>\(\ \frac{480}{x-8}hours\)</strong></p><p>Now, according to given condition:</p><p>\(\frac{480}{x-8}-\frac{480}{x} = 3\)</p><p>480x – 480 ( x – 8 )  = 3x ( x – 8 )</p><p><strong>3x<sup>2 </sup>&#8211; 24x – 3840  = 0.</strong>   Where x= speed of train in km/h</p><p>On solving we get x = 32</p><p><strong>This is the required quadratic equation^{<}</strong></p> <p><strong>Excercise 4.2</strong></p><p><strong><em>Question 1:Find the roots of the following quadratic equations by factorisation:</em></strong></p><p><strong>i) \(x^{2} – 3x – 10 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\(x^{2} – 3x – 10 = 0 \)</p><p>\(x^{2} – 5x + 2x – 10 = 0 \)</p><p>\(x(x -5) + 2(x – 5) = 0 \)</p><p>(x -5)(x + 2) = 0</p><p>x =5,x = -2</p><p><strong>ii) \(2x^{2} + x – 6 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\(2x^{2} + 4x -3x – 6 = 0 \)</p><p>\(2x(x +2) - 3(x + 2) = 0 \)</p><p>\(2x - 3)(x +2)  = 0 \)</p><p>\(x = \frac{3}{3},x = -2\)</p><p><strong>iii) \(\sqrt{2}x^{2} + 7x + 5\sqrt{2} = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\(\sqrt{2}x^{2} + 2x + 5x + 5\sqrt{2} = 0 \)</p><p>\(\sqrt{2}x(x + \sqrt{2}) + 5(x  + \sqrt{2}) = 0 \)</p><p>\((\sqrt{2}x + 5)(x + \sqrt{2}) = 0 \)</p><p>\(x = \frac{-5}{\sqrt{2}},x = -\sqrt{2}\)</p><p><strong>iv) \(2x^{2} – x + \frac{1}{8} = 0\)</strong></p><p>\(2x^{2} – x + \frac{1}{8} = 0\)</p><p>\(2x^{2} – \frac{x}{2} – \frac{x}{2} + \frac{1}{8} = 0\)</p><p>\(\frac{x}{2}(4x - 1) – \frac{1}{8}(4x -1 )  = 0\)</p><p>\((\frac{x}{2} - \frac{1}{8} )(4x - 1)  = 0\)</p><p>\(x = \frac{1}{4},x = \frac{1}{4}\)</p><p><strong>v) \(100 x^{2} – 20x + 1 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\(100 x^{2} – 10x -10x + 1 = 0 \)</p><p>\(10x(10x - 1) – 1(10x - 1) = 0 \)</p><p>\(10x(10x -1) - 1(10x – 1) = 0 \)</p><p>\(x = \frac{1}{10},x = \frac{1}{10}\)</p><p><strong>Question 3:Find two numbers whose sum is 27 and product is 182</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>According to given condition:</p><p><strong> x . y = 182 ……………………….. (1)</strong></p><p>And,</p><p><strong> x + y = 27 ……………………………. (2)</strong></p><p>Substituting equation (2) in (1) we get:</p><p>x(27 &#8211; x) = 182</p><p>(or)</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>&#8211; 27x + 182= 0</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>– (16 + 9)x + 144= 0</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>&#8211; 16x – 9x + 144= 0</p><p>x(x &#8211; 14) &#8211; 9(x &#8211; 13) = 0</p><p><strong>Therefore, x = 14 or   x = 13</strong></p><p><strong>So, if first number (x) is 14 then second number (y) will be (27 -16) = 13</strong></p><p>(or)</p><p><strong>If first number is(x) 13 then second number(y) will be (27-13) = 14.</strong></p><p>so the two numbers are 13 and 14</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q7.Find two consecutive positive integers, sum of whose squares is 365.</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let,  1<sup>st</sup> number be <strong>x</strong></p><p>Therefore,     second number will be <strong>(x+1)</strong></p><p>According to the given condition:</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ (x + 1)<sup>2 </sup>= 365</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ x<sup>2 </sup>+ 2x + 1 = 365</p><p>2x<sup>2 </sup>+ 2x – 364 = 0</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ x &#8211; 182 = 0</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ (14 &#8211; 13) x &#8211; 240 = 0</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ 14x &#8211; 13x &#8211; 240 = 0</p><p>x(x + 14) &#8211; 13(x + 16) = 0</p><p>(x &#8211; 13) (x + 14) = 0</p><p>Therefore,</p><p><strong>x= 13   (or)   x=  -14</strong></p><p>Since, the positive integers can’t be -14</p><p><strong>Hence two consecutive positive integers are 13 and 14. </strong></p><p><strong>Q.5 The altitude of a right triangle is 7 cm less than its base. If the hypotenuse is 13 cm, findthe other two sides</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>In right angled triangle ABC:</p><p>Let,        length of altitude = x cm</p><p>Therefore                   base = (x + 7) cm</p><p>Now, according to the given condition:</p><p>(AB)<sup>2  </sup>+ (AC)<sup>2 </sup>= (BC)<sup>2 </sup>  (From Pythagoras theorem)</p><p>(x)<sup>2  </sup>+ (x+7)<sup>2 </sup>= (13)<sup>2</sup></p><p>x<sup>2  </sup>+ x<sup>2 </sup>+ 14x + 49 = 169</p><p>2x<sup>2 </sup>+ 14x – 120 = 0</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ 7x &#8211; 60 = 0</p><p><strong>This is required quadratic equation, on further solving this equation:</strong></p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ 7x – 60 = 0</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ (12 &#8211; 5)x – 60 = 0</p><p>x<sup>2 </sup>+ 12x &#8211; 5x &#8211; 60 = 0</p><p>x(x + 12) &#8211; 5(x + 12) = 0</p><p>(x + 12) (x &#8211; 5) = 0</p><p>Therefore, <strong>x = -12 (or) x = 5</strong></p><p>Since length cannot be negative. Therefore, neglecting -12cm</p><p><strong>Hence the length of altitude = 5 cm and length of the base = 12cm</strong></p><p><strong>Q.6 A cottage industry produces a certain number of pottery articles in a day. It was observedon a particular day that the cost of production of each article (in rupees) was 3 more thantwice the number of articles produced on that day. If the total cost of production on thatday was ` 90, find the number of articles produced and the cost of each article.</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let the cost of each article be x and number of articles be y</p><p>According tot the question:</p><p>\(x = 2y + 3 \)</p><p>\( x y = 90  \)</p><p> \((2y + 3)y = 90\)</p><p>\((2y^{2} + 3y - 90 = 0\)</p><p>\((2y^{2} + 15y - 12y - 90 = 0\)</p><p>\((y(2y + 15) - 6(2y + 15) = 0\)</p><p>\((2y + 15)(y - 6) = 0\)</p><p>so no of articles produced 6 and cost of  each article 15</p><p><strong>Exercise 4.3</strong></p><p><strong><em>Find the roots of the following quadratic equations, if they exist, by the method ofcompleting the square:</strong></em></p><p><strong>i)\(2x^{2} – 7x + 3 = 0\)</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:Its advisable to make coefficients of \(x^{2}\) 1 ,its not compulsory but we will stick to that approach,if you dont want to make coefiicient of \(x^{2}\) 1,make it a perfect square</strong></p><p>\(2x^{2} – 7x + 3 = 0\)</p><p>\(x^{2} – \frac{7x}{2} + \frac{3}{2} = 0\)</p><p>\((x – \frac{7}{4})^{2} + \frac{3}{2} - \frac{49}{16} = 0\)</p><p>\((x – \frac{7}{4})^{2} + \frac{24 - 49}{16}  = 0\)</p><p>\((x – \frac{7}{4})^{2} + \frac{-25}{16}  = 0\)</p><p>\((x – \frac{7}{4})^{2}  =  \frac{25}{16}\)</p><p>\((x – \frac{7}{4}) =  \frac{5}{4}\)</p><p>\(x  =  \frac{5}{4} +  \frac{7}{4}\)</p><p>\(x  =  3 \)</p><p>\((x = \frac{-5 + 7}{4}) \)</p><p>\((x = \frac{1}{2}) \)</p><p><strong>ii)\(2x^{2} + x – 4 = 0\)</strong></p><p>\(2x^{2} + x – 4 = 0\)</p><p>\(x^{2} + \frac{x}{2} – 2 = 0\)</p><p>\( (x + \frac{1}{4})^{2} – 2 - \frac{1}{16} = 0\)</p><p>\( (x + \frac{1}{4})^{2} – \frac{33}{16} = 0\)</p><p>\( (x + \frac{1}{4})^{2} = \frac{33}{16} \)</p><p>\( (x + \frac{1}{4}) = \pm \sqrt{\frac{33}{16}} \)</p><p>\( x  = {\frac{\sqrt{33} - 1}{4}}  \)</p><p>\( x  = {\frac{-\sqrt{33} - 1}{4}} \)</p><p><strong>iii)\(4x^{2} + 4\sqrt{3}x + 3 = 0\)</strong></p><p>\(4x^{2} + 4\sqrt{3}x + 3 = 0\)</p><p>In this question we will not make coefficient of \(x^{2} = 1\) as there are 2 ways to solve quadratic equations bylcompleting the square,one is making coefficient of \(x^{2} = 1\) and other has coefficient of x^{2} as perfect square which is the case since 4 is a perfect square</p><p>\( (2x + \sqrt{3})^{2} + 3 - 3 = 0\)</p><p>\( (x  = -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \)</p><p>But this is only one root ,where is the root actually the given equation has equal roots</p><p><strong>iv \( 2x^{2} + x + 4 = 0 \)</strong></p><p> \( 2x^{2} + x + 4 = 0 \) </p><p> \( x^{2} + \frac{x}{2} + 2 = 0 \) </p><p> \( (x + \frac{1}{4})^{2} + 2 - \frac{1}{4} = 0 \) </p><p> \( (x + \frac{1}{4})^{2} +  \frac{7}{4} = 0 \) </p><p> \( x + \frac{1}{4}  =   \frac{\sqrt{-7}}{4} = 0 \) </p><p>Since we dont know the square root of a negative integer ,the roots doesnt exist.When you will reach higher classes you will get to know how to solve from here</p><p><strong>Question 2:Find the roots of the quadratic equations given in Q.1 above by applying the quadraticformula.</strong></p><p>i)\(2x^{2} – 7x + 3 = 0\)</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>The roots using quadratic formula are given by:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\)</p><p>On putting the values of a, b and c in quadratic formulae we get:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-(-7)+\sqrt{(-7)^{2}-4(2\times 3)}}{2\times 2}\)   and   \(x=\frac{-(-7)-\sqrt{(-7)^{2}-4(2\times 3)}}{2\times 2}\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\(x=\frac{7+\sqrt{49-24}}{4}\)   and   \(x=\frac{7-\sqrt{49-24}}{4}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{7+5}{4}\)   and   \(x=\frac{7-5}{4}\)</p><p>\(x= 3\)   and   \(x=\frac{1}{2}\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii))\(2x^{2} + x – 4 = 0\)</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>The roots using quadratic formula are given by:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\)</p><p>On putting the values of a, b and c in quadratic formulae we get:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-(1)+\sqrt{(1)^{2}-4(2\times -4)}}{2\times 2}\)   and   \(x=\frac{(1)-\sqrt{(1)^{2}-4(2\times -4)}}{2\times 2}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{-1+ \sqrt{33}}{4}\)   and   \(x=\frac{1-\sqrt{33}}{4}\)</p><p>iii)\(4x^{2} + 4\sqrt{3}x + 3 = 0\)</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>The roots using quadratic formula are given by:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\)</p><p>On putting the values of a, b and c in quadratic formulae we get:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-(4\sqrt{3})+\sqrt{(4\sqrt{3})^{2}-4(4\times 3)}}{2\times 4}\)   and   \(x=\frac{-(4\sqrt{3}) -\sqrt{(4\sqrt{3})^{2}-4(4\times 3)}}{2\times 4}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{-(4\sqrt{3})+\sqrt{48-48}}{2\times 4}\)   and   \(x=\frac{-(4\sqrt{3}) -\sqrt{48-48}}{2\times 4}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{-4\sqrt{3}}{2\times 4}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{-\sqrt{3}}{2}\)</p><p>iii)\(2x^{2} + x + 4 = 0\)</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>The roots using quadratic formula are given by:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\)</p><p>On putting the values of a, b and c in quadratic formulae we get:</p><p>\( D = b^{2}-4ac \)</p><p>\( D = 1^{2}-4\times 2\times 4 \)</p><p>Since D is negative,the roots doesnt exist</p><p><strong>Question 3:Find the roots of the following equations:</strong></p><p>\( x - ( \frac{1}{x} ) \) = 3,\(x \ne 3\)</p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>\(( \frac {x^{2} - 1} {x}   = 3 \)</p><p>\(  x^{2} - 1    = 3x \)</p><p>\(  x^{2}   -3x -1  = 0 \)</p><p>The roots using quadratic formula are given by:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\)</p><p>On putting the values of a, b and c in quadratic formulae we get:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-(-1) + \sqrt{(-3)^{2}-4(1\times -1)}} {2\times 1}\)   and   \(x=\frac{-(-1) - \sqrt{(-3)^{2}-4(1\times -1)}} {2\times 1}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{ 1 + \sqrt{13}} {2}\)   and   \(x=\frac{ 1 - \sqrt{13}} {2}\)</p><p><strong>ii)\(( \frac{1}{x + 4} - \frac{1}{x - 7})  = \frac {11}{30} ,x \ne -4,7 \)</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>\( \frac { (x -7) - (x + 4)} {  (x + 4)(x - 7) }   = \frac {11}{30} \)</p><p>\(  30\times -11 =   11\times (x^{2} -7x + 4x - 28) \)</p><p>\(  -330 =   (11x^{2} -77x + 44x - 308) \)</p><p>\(  11x^{2} -33x + 22 = 0 \)</p><p>\(  x^{2} -3x + 2 = 0 \)</p><p>\(  x^{2} -2x -x + 2 = 0 \)</p><p>\(  x(x -2) -1(x - 2) = 0 \)</p><p>\(  (x -2)(x - 1) = 0 \)</p><p>\(  x = 2  or   x = 1  \)</p><p><strong>Question 4:The sum of the reciprocals of Rehman’s ages, (in years) 3 years ago and 5 years fromnow is 1/3.Find his present age.</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let the present age of rehman be x years</p><p>Now according to the question</p><p> \( (\frac{1}{x - 3} + \frac{1}{x + 5})  = \frac {1}{3} \)</p><p> \( 3\times (x + 5 + x - 3)   = (x -3)(x + 5) \)</p><p> \( 3\times (2x + 2 )   = x^{2} + 2x - 15) \)</p><p> \(  x^{2} - 4x - 21 = 0 \)</p><p> \(  x^{2} - 4x - 21 = 0 \)</p><p> \(  (x - 7)(x + 4) = 0 \)</p><p>x = 7 years </p><p>so the present age of Rehman is 7 years</p><p><strong><em>Question 5:In a class test, the sum of Shefali’s marks in Mathematics and English is 30. Had she got2 marks more in Mathematics and 3 marks less in English, the product of their markswould have been 210. Find her marks in the two subjects.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let her marks in mathematics be x and amrks in english be y</p><p>According to the question:</p><p>\(x + y = 30 \) ....(1)  </p><p>\((x + 2)(y - 3) = 210\) </p><p>Substituting the value of x from eq 1</p><p>\(xy -3x + 2y -6 -210 = 0\)</p><p>\((30 - y)y -3(30 - y) + 2y -216 = 0\)</p><p>\(30y - y^{2} - 90 + 3y + 2y - 216 = 0\)</p><p>\(35y -y^{2} -306 = 0 \)</p><p>\(y^{2}  -35y + 306 = 0\)</p><p>\((y - 18)(y - 17)\)</p><p>if y = 18,x = 12</p><p>if y = 17,x = 13</p><p><strong><em>Question 6:The diagonal of a rectangular field is 60 metres more than the shorter side. If the longerside is 30 metres more than the shorter side, find the sides of the field.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let the shorter side be x,longer side = x + 30</p><p>Now according to the question:</p><p>\(  x^{2} + (x + 30)^{2} = (x + 60)^{2}  \)<p>\(  x^{2} + x^{2} + 900 + 60x = x^{2} + 3600 + 120x  \)<p>\(  x^{2} -60x - 2700 = 0  \)<p>\(  x^{2} -60x - 2700 = 0  \)<p>\(  (x + 90) (x - 30) = 0  \)<p>So the length of shoter side is 30 m ,length of longer sode 60m and length of diagonal is 90m </p><p><strong><em>Question 7:The difference of squares of two numbers is 180. The square of the smaller number is 8times the larger number. Find the two numbers.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p> \(  x^{2} - y^{2} = 180  \)       ...(1)  </p><p> \(   y^{2} = 8x  \)               ...(2)  </p><p> \(  x^{2} - 8x - 180 = 0  \)       ...(3) </p><p> \(  (x -18)(x+10)  \)       ...(3)        </p><p>so two numbers are 18 and \( \sqrt{144} = 12 \) </p><p><strong><em>Question 8:A train travels 360 km at a uniform speed. If the speed had been 5 km/h more, it wouldhave taken 1 hour less for the same journey. Find the speed of the train.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let the spped be x km/hr,now according to the question:</p><p> \(   \frac{360}{x} - \frac{360}{x + 5} = 1                 \) </p><p> \(   360(x + 5 -x) = x(x+5)  \) </p><p> \(   x^{2} + 5x - 1800 = 0   \) </p><p> \(   (x - 40) (x + 45) = 0  \) </p><p> \(   x = 40 , x = -45 \) </p><p>so the speed of train is 40 km/hr </p><p><strong><em>Question 9:Two water taps together can fill a tank in  \( 9\frac{3}{8} \) hours. The tap of larger diameter takes 10 hours less than the smaller one to fill the tank separately. Find the time in which each tap can separately fill the tank.</em></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>Let the tank capacity be l litres and the speed with which taps can fill water in them are x and y litres/hour</p><p>According to the question:</p><p>When both taps will run they can fill x + y litres in one hour</p><p>1 litre can be filled in \( \frac{1}{x + y} \)</p><p>l litre can be filled in \( \frac{l}{x + y} = \frac{75}{8} \)        </p><p>\( l = \frac{75}{8}(x + y) \)  ...(1)      </p><p>\(  \frac{l}{x}  - \frac{l}{y}  = 10                   ...(1)     \)</p><p>we have to find out \(  \frac{l}{x} and \frac{l}{y}  \)    </p><p>Putting the value of l </p><p>\(    l(y - x) = 10xy        \)           ....(2)</p><p>\(     75(x + y)(y - x) =     80xy                   \)           ....(2)</p><p>\(     -75(x^{2} - y^{2}) = 80xy                   \)           ....(2)</p><p>\(    75x^{2} + (80y)x - (75y^{2}) = 0                \) .......(4)</p><p> now if we can find a relation in x and y then we can easily find \frac{l}{x} and \frac{l}{y}  </p><p>The equation 4 is also a quadratic in x with a = 15,b = 16y and c = -15</p><p>\(    15x^{2} + (16y)x - (15y^{2}) = 0                \) .......(4)</p><p>\(x = \frac{-16y + 34y}{30} = \frac{18y}{30} = \frac{3y}{5} \)</p><p>Putting this in eq 1</p><p>\( 5l = \frac{75}{8}(8y) \)                           </p><p>\( \frac{l}{y} = 15 \)                           </p><p>\( \frac{l}{x} = 25 \)                           </p><p><strong>Note:This is a good question,variation of this question can come in exams,its advisable to give some time to understand this problem and how a equation involving both terms of x and y can also be viewed as a quadratic in one variable and therefore can be used to find a relation between two variables x and y</strong></p><p><strong><em>Question 9:An express train takes 1 hour less than a passenger train to travel 132 km betweenMysore and Bangalore (without taking into consideration the time they stop at intermediate stations). If the average speed of the express train is 11km/h more than that of the passenger train, find the average speed of the two trains.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let the speed of passenger train be x km/hr ,then speed of express train = x + 11 km/hr </p><p>Now,according to the question</p><p>\(  \frac{132}{x} - \frac{132}{x+11} = 1                   \)</p><p>\(  132\times 11 = x(x_+ 11)                   \)</p><p>\(  x^{2} + 11x -(11\times 11\times 22)                  \)</p><p>\((x - 33)(x + 44) = 0\) </p><p>so the speed of trains are 33 and 44 km/hr</p><p><strong><em>Question 10:Sum of the areas of two squares is 468 m2 . If the difference of their perimeters is 24 m,find the sides of the two squares.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>let sides of sqaures be x and y</p><p>Now according to the question:</p><p>\(4(x - y)= 24\)</p><p>x - y = 6</p><p>\(x^{2} + y^{2} = 468\)</p><p>\( (6 + y)^{2} + y^{2} = 468 \)</p><p>\( 36 + y^{2} + 12y + y^{2} = 468 \) </p><p>\(  y^{2} + 6y  - 216 = 0 \) </p><p>\(  (y + 18)(y - 12) = 0 \) </p><p>\( y = 12,x = 18 \)</p><p><strong>Exercise 4.4</strong></p><p><strong>Question 1:Find the nature of the roots of the following quadratic equations. If the real roots exist,find them?</strong></p><p><strong>i)\( 2x^{2} – 3x + 5 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\( D = b^{2} - 4ac \)</p><p>\( For the given equation:D = (-3)^{2} - 4\times 2\times 5 \)</p><p>\( D = 9 - 40 \)</p><p>\( D = -31 \)</p><p>Since D < 0,the given equation has no  real roots</p><p>On putting the values of a, b and c in quadratic formulae we get:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-(3)+\sqrt{(-3)^{2}-4(2\times )}}{2\times 2}\)   and   \(x=\frac{-(3)-\sqrt{(-3)^{2}-4(2\times 5)}}{2\times 2}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{-(3)+\sqrt{9-4(2\times )}}{2\times 2}\)   and   \(x=\frac{-(3)-\sqrt{(-3)^{2}-4(2\times 5)}}{2\times 2}\)</p><p><strong>ii)\( 3x^{2} – 4\sqrt{3}x + 4 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\( D = b^{2} - 4ac \)</p><p>\( D = (-4\sqrt{3})^{2} - 4\times 3\times 4 \)</p><p>\( D = 48 - 48 = 0 \)</p><p>Since D = 0,it has real and equal roots</p><p>On putting the values of a, b and c in quadratic formulae we get:</p><p>\(x=\frac{-(-4\sqrt{3})}{2\times 3}\)   and  \(x=\frac{-(-4\sqrt{3}) }{2\times 3}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{4\sqrt{3}}{6}\)   and  \(x=\frac{4\sqrt{3} }{6}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\)   </p><p><strong>iii)\( 2x^{2} – 6x + 3 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\( D = b^{2} - 4ac \)</p><p>\( D = (-6)^{2} - 4\times 2\times 3 \)</p><p>\( D = 36 - 24 = 12 \)</p><p>\(Since \sqrt{D} = \sqrt{12}= 2\sqrt{3} > 0\),it has real roots</p><p>On putting the values of a, b and c in quadratic formulae we get:</p><p>\(x=\frac{6 + 2\sqrt{3}}{2\times 2 }\)   and  \(x=\frac{6 - 2\sqrt{3}}{2\times 2 }\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{6 + 2\sqrt{3}}{4}\)   and  \(x=\frac{6 - 2\sqrt{3}}{4}\)</p><p>\(x=\frac{3 + \sqrt{3}}{2}\)   and  \(x=\frac{3 - \sqrt{3}}{2}\)</p><p><strong>Find the values of k for each of the following quadratic equations, so that they have twoequal roots?</strong></p><p><strong>i)\( 2x^{2} + kx + 3 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\( D = b^{2} - 4ac  = 0 \)</p><p>\( k^{2} - 4\times 2\times 3  = 0 \)</p><p>\( k^{2} - 4\times 2\times 3  = 0 \)</p><p>\( k^{2}                      = 24 \)</p><p>\( k                          = \pm \sqrt{24} \)</p><p>\( k                          = \pm 2\sqrt{6} \)</p><p><strong>ii)\( kx (x – 2) + 6 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\( kx^{2} - 2kx + 6 = 0 \)</strong></p><p>\( D = (-2k)^{2} - 4\times k\times 6  = 0 \)</p><p>\( 4k^{2} - 24k  = 0 \)</p><p>\( 4k(k  - 6)  = 0 \)</p><p> k =0 or k =6 </p><p>k cant be zero as it will not remain a quadratic equation so k = 6 </p><p><strong>Question 3:Is it possible to design a rectangular mango grove whose length is twice its breadth,and the area is 800 m 2 ? If so, find its length and breadth.</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let breadth be x and length be 2x </p> <p>Area = 800 </p> <p>\(2x^{2} = 800\) </p> <p>\(x^{2} = 400\) </p> <p>\(x     = 20\) </p> <p>so yes it is possible with length = 40  and breadth = 20 </p><p><strong><em>Is the following situation possible? If so, determine their present ages.The sum of the ages of two friends is 20 years. Four years ago, the product of their agesin years was 48.</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>Let ages be x and y </p><p>\(x  +  y = 20\)</p><p>\((x - 4)(y - 4) = 48\)</p><p>\((x - 4)(20 -x - 4) = 48\)</p><p>\((x - 4)(-x +16) = 48\)</p><p>\(-x^{2} + 16x + 4x  - 64 - 48 = 0\)</p><p>\(-x^{2} + 20x  - 122 = 0\)</p><p>\(x^{2}  - 20x  + 122 = 0\)</p><p>\(D= b^{2} - 4ac = 400 - 488 < 0 \)</p><p>Since \( D < 0 \),no real solution possible,hence the following situation not possible </p><p><strong><em>Is it possible to design a rectangular park of perimeter 80 m and area 400 m 2 ? If so, findits length and breadth</em></strong></p><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p><p>let length be x and breadth be y</p><p>\(2(x + y) = 80\)</p><p>\(x + y    = 40\)</p><p>\(xy       = 400\)</p><p>\(x(40 -x) = 400\)</p><p>\(40x -x^{2} = 400\)</p><p>\(x^{2} -40x + 400 = 0\)</p><p>\(x = 20,y =20\)</p><p><strong>Since the lengths are equal it will become a square and square is a special type of rectangle,so its possible</strong></p><div id="disqus_thread"></div><script>       var disqus_config = function () {        //this.page.url = 'http://www.ncertsolved.com/solutions/quadratic-equations';   